5. Q&A SECTION - 50 QUESTIONS (SHORT ANSWERS)
================================================================================

Read these before the presentation. During Q&A, you can reference these answers!

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 1: ARCHITECTURE & DESIGN
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q1: Why microservices instead of monolithic?
A: Three reasons: (1) Separation of concerns - each service has one job,
   (2) Independent scaling - scale prediction service without touching training,
   (3) Fault isolation - if training crashes, predictions still work.

Q2: Why Docker containers?
A: Three benefits: (1) Consistency - runs same everywhere, (2) Isolation - no
   library conflicts, (3) Easy deployment - one docker-compose.yml starts everything.

Q3: Isn't 13 containers too many?
A: Each has clear purpose: 6 ML services, 4 Airflow, 2 monitoring, 1 UI. Need
   all for complete MLOps. Removing any loses important functionality.

Q4: How do containers communicate?
A: Shared Docker network (mlops_network, bridge type). Containers find each other
   by name. Example: Gateway calls "http://prediction_service:5003". Docker DNS
   resolves names automatically.

Q5: What if one container crashes?
A: Others keep running. Docker health checks every 30s, auto-restarts failed
   containers. Microservices architecture = resilient system.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 2: ML MODEL & TRAINING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q6: Why LSTM instead of simpler model?
A: Text has word order. "Samsung Galaxy phone" ≠ "phone Galaxy Samsung". LSTM
   reads sequentially and remembers context. Naive Bayes = 65% accuracy, LSTM = 80%.

Q7: Why LSTM not Transformer (BERT)?
A: BERT is powerful but slow + big. BERT needs GPU, takes hours. LSTM trains in
   10 minutes on CPU. For 27 categories, LSTM is good enough. Balance: simplicity
   vs accuracy.

Q8: What happens inside LSTM?
A: 4 layers: (1) Input: 10 numbers, (2) Embedding: each number → 128-dim vector,
   (3) LSTM: 128 units, reads sequence + remembers context, (4) Dense: 27 neurons,
   softmax gives probabilities. Highest = answer.

Q9: What is preprocessing?
A: Cleaning text before model sees it. 6 steps: remove HTML, lowercase, remove
   numbers/symbols, tokenize (split words), remove French stopwords, lemmatize
   (running → run). Makes data consistent.

Q10: What is tokenization and padding?
A: Tokenization: words → numbers (vocab 10,000). "Samsung"=42, "galaxy"=17.
    Padding: make all sequences length 10. Shorter? Add zeros. Longer? Cut.
    Neural networks need fixed-size input.

Q11: How do you measure model quality?
A: Two metrics: (1) Accuracy - how often correct (80% = right 8/10 times),
   (2) Loss - how wrong (lower better). Split data: 70% train, 15% validation,
   15% test. Check on unseen data to prevent overfitting.

Q12: What is overfitting? How prevent?
A: Model memorizes training data instead of learning patterns. Gets 100% on
   training, fails on new data. Prevent: (1) Test on separate data, (2) Don't
   train too long (stop at 10 epochs), (3) Could add dropout but 10 epochs enough.

Q13: Why 10 epochs?
A: Tested different numbers. 5 epochs: still learning. 20 epochs: stopped improving
   at 12. 10 epochs: good accuracy without wasting time. Hyperparameter tuning by
   experimentation.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 3: MICROSERVICES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q14: What does API Gateway do?
A: Three jobs: (1) Authentication - checks token with Auth Service, rejects invalid,
   (2) Routing - sends requests to right service based on URL path, (3) Logging -
   Prometheus tracks every request. Centralized control = secure + observable.

Q15: How does JWT authentication work?
A: Login: check SHA-256 password hash → generate 64-char random token → return
   to browser. Browser saves in localStorage. Every request: send token in
   Authorization header ("Bearer <token>"). Gateway asks Auth: valid? Yes = continue,
   No = 401 error. Re-login = old token deleted.

Q16: Why hash passwords with SHA-256?
A: Security. Database hack? They see hash, not real password. "admin123" →
   "8c6976e5b5410...918". One-way (cannot reverse). Login: hash input, compare
   to stored hash. Match = correct password.

Q17: Authentication vs Authorization?
A: Authentication = WHO you are (username + password check). Authorization =
   WHAT you can do (permission check). Both "admin" and "user" authenticate,
   but only "admin" authorized to retrain. RBAC = Role-Based Access Control.

Q18: How does prediction service work?
A: 10 steps: Browser → Gateway → Auth check → Gateway → Prediction Service →
   preprocess (clean, tokenize, pad) → LSTM predict → 27 probabilities → find
   highest → map to name → return to Gateway → return to browser → show result.
   Takes < 1 second.

Q19: Can multiple users predict simultaneously?
A: Yes. Flask handles concurrent requests in separate threads. Model loaded once
   at startup, shared by all requests. 10 simultaneous users? Flask queues and
   processes. High traffic? Start multiple prediction containers + load balancer.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 4: MLFLOW & EXPERIMENT TRACKING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q20: What is MLflow? Why need it?
A: Experiment tracking tool. Saves every training run automatically: hyperparameters,
   accuracy, loss, time taken. Without it: manual spreadsheet. Also model registry:
   save multiple versions, mark best one. Critical for reproducibility + comparison.

Q21: What does MLflow track?
A: Three types: (1) Parameters - epochs, batch_size, max_words, embedding_dim, etc.
   (2) Metrics - train/val loss, train/val accuracy, (3) Artifacts - model.h5,
   tokenizer config, mapper.pkl. Also tracks: who, when, duration.

Q22: How use MLflow in training?
A: Code integration: mlflow.start_run() → log params with mlflow.log_param() →
   custom MLflowCallback logs loss/accuracy after each epoch → mlflow.log_artifact()
   for model file → mlflow.end_run(). All automatic in training service.

Q23: Can you compare training runs?
A: Yes. MLflow UI (localhost:5000) shows table of all runs. Sort by accuracy to
   find best. Click run = see all params + metrics. Compare two runs side-by-side:
   MLflow shows differences. Example: "Run 1: 10 epochs, 78%. Run 2: 15 epochs, 80%."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 5: AIRFLOW & ORCHESTRATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q24: What is Airflow? Why use it?
A: Workflow orchestration. Runs tasks in order automatically. Retraining = 4 steps
   that must run sequentially. If training fails, don't reload model. Airflow
   manages scheduling + error handling. Define DAG (task chain), Airflow executes.

Q25: What is a DAG?
A: Directed Acyclic Graph. Directed = tasks have order (arrows). Acyclic = no loops.
   Simple: chain of tasks. Our retrain DAG: Task1 → Task2 → Task3 → Task4.
   Airflow runs one by one. Any fails? Stop, mark DAG failed.

Q26: How does retraining work?
A: Admin clicks "Start Retraining" → Dashboard → Gateway → check admin role →
   Gateway calls Airflow REST API → trigger retrain_pipeline DAG → Airflow runs
   4 tasks: (1) Data Service preprocess, (2) Training Service train (background),
   (3) Poll every 10s: done? (max 1 hour), (4) Prediction Service reload model.
   Fully automatic.

Q27: What if training fails?
A: Airflow detects failure, stops DAG. Later tasks don't run. Example: training
   crashes at epoch 5 → Task 3 sees error → marks failed → stops. Task 4 (reload)
   doesn't run. Old model stays loaded = safe. Airflow UI shows error, can retry
   manually after fix.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 6: MONITORING (Prometheus & Grafana)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q28: How does monitoring work?
A: Prometheus scrapes /metrics endpoint on all Flask services every 15s. Stores
   numbers in time-series DB. Grafana connects to Prometheus via PromQL, makes
   charts. Custom dashboard shows real-time: request counts, latency, health,
   confidence.

Q29: What metrics do you track?
A: 8 types: (1) Request count per service, (2) Request latency (ms), (3) Service
   health (up/down), (4) Predictions per category, (5) Prediction confidence (avg),
   (6) Inference latency, (7) Training status (running/idle), (8) Training loss/accuracy.
   All automatic via prometheus_client library.

Q30: Why monitoring important?
A: Visibility. Without it: blind. Monitoring shows: slow service? Low confidence?
   Service crash? In production: connect to alerts (latency > 500ms → SMS engineer).
   For this project: dashboards show everything visually.

Q31: What is PromQL?
A: Query language for Prometheus. Like SQL but for metrics. Grafana uses PromQL
   to get data. Example: avg request latency last 5 min = "rate(duration_sum[5m]) /
   rate(duration_count[5m])". Powerful but complex. We use pre-built queries.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 7: DATA & DVC
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q32: Why DVC instead of Git for data?
A: Data = 5.6 GB. Git designed for code (small text files). 5.6 GB in Git =
   huge repo, slow clone. DVC designed for big files. Git stores tiny metadata
   file (data.dvc, 200 bytes), actual data stored separately. Keeps Git small + fast.

Q33: How does DVC track pipeline?
A: dvc.yaml defines 3 stages: data_import, preprocess, train. For each: command
   to run, input files, output files. "dvc repro" checks: inputs changed? Yes =
   re-run. No = use cache. Like Make but for data. Saves time: data unchanged?
   Skip preprocessing.

Q34: Where does data come from?
A: Kaggle. Rakuten dataset: French product descriptions, 27 categories. Two parts:
   CSV (text + labels), images (one per product). Total 5.6 GB. We use only text.
   Images available but not used (could build image classifier later).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 8: CI/CD (GitHub Actions)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q35: What is CI/CD? Why important?
A: Continuous Integration/Delivery. CI = tests run automatically on every push.
   CD = code always ready to deploy. GitHub Actions: push → trigger workflow →
   run flake8 (linting) + pytest (tests) + Docker build. All pass = code good.
   Prevents bugs in production.

Q36: What tests do you run?
A: Two types: (1) Flake8 linting - check syntax, undefined vars, unused imports,
   line length. (2) Pytest unit tests - test data loading, preprocessing, tokenizer,
   model architecture, auth logic. Also check: no large binary files committed.

Q37: What is flake8?
A: Python linting tool. Checks: syntax errors, undefined variables, unused imports,
   lines > 127 chars. Keeps code clean + consistent. All team members same style.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 9: SECURITY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q38: What security measures?
A: Four: (1) SHA-256 password hashing (never plaintext), (2) JWT token authentication
   (every request needs valid token), (3) RBAC (admin vs user permissions),
   (4) Token invalidation on re-login (prevents token theft). Also CI/CD checks
   for committed secrets.

Q39: Can someone steal a token?
A: If intercepted (network sniffing), yes - usable until invalidated. Prevention:
   HTTPS (encrypt communication). This project: HTTP on localhost. Production:
   add HTTPS + token expiration (auto-invalid after 1 hour).

Q40: Admin vs user roles?
A: User: predict + view history only. Cannot retrain, no Retrain tab, no Users tab.
   Admin: everything (predict, retrain, manage users). Auth Service stores role
   in DB. Login response includes role. Gateway checks role before admin actions.
   RBAC implementation.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 10: TROUBLESHOOTING & "WHAT IF"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q41: What if prediction service crashes?
A: User gets error (HTTP 503 Service Unavailable). Docker health check detects,
   auto-restarts in 10-30s. Meanwhile: no predictions, but training + monitoring
   still work. After restart: predictions work again. Fault isolation.

Q42: What if you want category 28?
A: Must retrain completely. Output layer = 27 neurons (one per category). Category 28
   needs 28 neurons = architecture change. Steps: (1) Add category 28 to data,
   (2) Update mapper.pkl, (3) Change code to num_classes=28, (4) Retrain from
   scratch, (5) Deploy new model. Old model cannot handle 28 without retrain.

Q43: What if training takes > 1 hour?
A: Airflow DAG timeout = 1 hour max. > 1 hour = task marked failed. Fix: (1) Increase
   timeout in DAG config, OR (2) Use GPU/stronger server. This project: 10 epochs
   = ~10 minutes. 1 hour = plenty.

Q44: How deploy to production?
A: Changes needed: (1) HTTPS not HTTP, (2) Cloud DB (AWS PostgreSQL) not SQLite,
   (3) Token expiration (1 hour), (4) Load balancer for prediction service,
   (5) Cloud storage (S3) for DVC, (6) Monitoring alerts (email on failure),
   (7) Kubernetes not docker-compose, (8) Central logging (ELK stack). Foundation
   ready, just make production-grade.

Q45: What if two admins retrain simultaneously?
A: Airflow: one DAG instance at a time (default). Admin 1 starts = DAG "running".
   Admin 2 clicks = Airflow rejects "DAG already running". Admin 2 must wait.
   Prevents conflicts. Sequential retraining = safer.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GROUP 11: GENERAL PROJECT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q46: How long to build this?
A: (Answer honestly based on your timeline. Example:)
   ~4-6 weeks. Week 1: planning + learning MLOps/Docker. Week 2-3: ML model +
   preprocessing. Week 3-4: microservices + Docker. Week 5: monitoring + CI/CD.
   Week 6: testing + documentation + presentation prep.

Q47: Most difficult part?
A: (Choose what was actually hard. Examples:)
   Option 1: Connecting all services together. Docker networking, token auth,
   debugging API calls took most time.
   Option 2: Understanding Airflow. DAGs, task dependencies, REST API were new
   concepts. Took several tries to get retraining workflow right.

Q48: What would you do differently?
A: If restarting: (1) Plan architecture first (draw diagrams before coding),
   (2) Write tests from beginning not end, (3) Document as I go not at end.
   Would save time + reduce bugs.

Q49: What did you learn?
A: Five things: (1) How to deploy ML models in production, (2) Microservices
   architecture benefits + challenges, (3) Docker + docker-compose for complex
   systems, (4) Monitoring with Prometheus/Grafana, (5) Integrating multiple
   tools (MLflow, Airflow, DVC) into cohesive system. Real-world MLOps experience.

Q50: Can this handle production traffic?
A: Architecture = production-ready. But need changes for high traffic: multiple
   prediction containers + load balancer, Kubernetes for orchestration + auto-scaling,
   managed DB not SQLite, caching (Redis), CDN for UI. Core design solid, just
   scale horizontally + add production infrastructure.


