6. EMERGENCY QUICK REFERENCE
================================================================================

SCENARIO 1: Service is RED (unhealthy)
SAY: "This demonstrates health checks. Core functionality still works due to
     microservices architecture."
DO: Continue presentation. If NOT prediction service, demo still works. Point
    out fault isolation.

SCENARIO 2: Prediction fails
SAY: "Let me try again. This shows error handling in the system."
DO: Click "Classify" again. Still fails? Show History panel with past predictions.
    Move on calmly.

SCENARIO 3: Website won't load
SAY: "Network issue. Let me show architecture diagrams while we troubleshoot."
DO: Skip to diagrams. Spend more time explaining architecture. Use screenshots
    if available.

SCENARIO 4: Forgot what to say
DO: Look at script (on laptop, not projector). Take sip of water (3-second pause).
    Say "Let me show you the next diagram" → scroll down. Audience doesn't know
    your plan.

SCENARIO 5: Very technical question you don't understand
SAY: "That's a detailed question. To give accurate answer, I'd need to check
     the implementation. What I can tell you is [general concept]. We can discuss
     details after."

SCENARIO 6: Accidentally clicked "Start Retraining"
SAY: "I've triggered the retraining workflow. It runs in background without
     affecting predictions. Airflow is orchestrating it now."
DO: Continue normally. This actually shows the system works!

SCENARIO 7: Network/Internet down
DO: System runs on localhost - doesn't need internet! If Docker network issue:
    restart (make stop && make start). While restarting: show diagrams, explain
    architecture verbally.

GENERAL PRINCIPLES:
1. Stay calm - audience doesn't know what was supposed to happen
2. Acknowledge, don't apologize excessively
3. Show your knowledge even if demo fails
4. Read from script if you forget
5. Technical glitch ≠ lack of understanding


